<section xml:id="sec-spherical-coords" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Spherical Coordinates</title>

  <p> It is not always easy to visualize functions with spherical coordinates.
    Thankully Mathematica makes it easy with <c>SphericalPlot[ ]</c>. We just need 
    a function <m>\rho(\theta, \phi)</m> determined by angles <m>\theta</m> and
    <m>phi</m>. Let's try one. </p>

    <p>
      <c>SphericalPlot3D[Sin[Theta]^2*Cos[Phi]-Sin[Phi],{Theta,-2Pi,2Pi},{Phi,0,Pi}]</c>
    </p>

    <figure>
        <image source="MakerCampus_Logo (3).jpg" width="50%" />
    </figure>

    <example>
        <title>Spherical Plots</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Try graphing the following using <c>ParametricPlot[ ]</c>: 
        
            <m>r(t) = \lt e^{\cos{3\theta}},  e^{-\sin{t}} \gt </m> 
               
            <m> r(t) = \lt 2-\sin(2t), 3 + 2\cos{t} \gt </m>
        </p>
          
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>f'(x) = 15x^4-7</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
