            We use the power, sum,
            and constant multiple rules and find that the derivative is <m>f'(x) = 15x^4-7</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>

    <example>
        <title>Differentiating a polynomial</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a Mathematica function that converts rectangular 
            coordinates to spherical coordinates. Then use your function to
             convert the following coordinates to spherical coordinates.

             <m> (-1,3,4) </m>

             <m>(\sqrt{3}, -3, 2)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>f'(x) = 15x^4-7</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We use the power, sum,
            and constant multiple rules and find that the derivative is <m>f'(x) = 15x^4-7</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>

    <p> The "bumpy sphere‚Äù with an equation in spherical coordinates is  
        <m>\rho = a+b\cos(m\theta)sin(n\phi)</m>, with  <m>\theta \in [0, 2\phi]</m> 
        and <m>\phi \in [0,\pi]</m>,  where  <m>a</m> and  <m>b</m>  are positive 
        numbers and  <m>m</m>  and  <m>n</m>  are positive integers, may be used in 
        applied mathematics to model tumor growth.
    </p>
    
      <exercise>
       Plot the bumpy sphere with <m>a = 14, b =2</m>, and <m>n = 6</m> along with the 
